   <text>
      <body>
         <div type="letter">
            <pb n="1" facs="uoedh_hl_h.2722_1.jpg"/>
            <opener>
               <address>
                  <addrLine>29, Delamere Terrace</addrLine>
                  <addrLine>Westbourne Square.W.</addrLine>
               </address>
               <dateline>
                  <date when="1897-04-01">1.4.97</date>
               </dateline>
               <salute>My dear Hardy</salute>
            </opener>

            <p>It was the "World" which maddened me into taking up the cudgels in "<orgName
                  ref="#ps:StJamesGazette"><choice><abbr>the St. J.G.</abbr><expan>St James
                        Gazette</expan></choice></orgName>" Tell me whether the letter, which I sent
               you last night, has cheered you up at all? Sheer unjust deÂ­traction does lower one's
               vitality for the moment; it is an actual poison. My impression is that that review
               was written by some smart <pb n="2" facs="uoedh_hl_h.2722_2.jpg"/> feather-headed
               woman, grinding some axe of her own. If one only knew who wrote these things, very
               often the whole sting of them would fade away. For instance, the review of "<ref
                  target="#bib:Hardy1891_Tess">Tess</ref>" which annoyed us all so much, as soon as
               one found out that <persName ref="#ps:LeonoraBlancheAlleyne"> M<hi rend="superscript"
                     >rs</hi> Andrew Lang</persName> had written it, - what did it matter? I dread
               more than any other <pb n="3" facs="uoedh_hl_h.2722_3.jpg"/> "sign of the times" the
               prominence which women are getting in journalism, because women who scribble are
               always ignorant, generally malevolent, and entirely unscrupulous. That responsibility
               to keep high the standard of the Best, for its own sake, which is the very spirit
               &amp; blood of an artist-man, seems to <pb n="4" facs="uoedh_hl_h.2722_4.jpg"/> be
               incomprehensible to a woman.</p>

            <closer>
               <salute>Ever yours sincerely</salute>
               <signed>Edmund Gosse</signed>
            </closer>

            <postscript>
               <p>When, at the end of my second article, I spoke of "the <persName
                     ref="#ps:AmeliaBooth">Amelias</persName> &amp; the <persName
                     ref="#ps:MarciaCoryston">Marcias</persName>," I meant <persName
                     ref="#ps:HenryFielding">Fielding</persName>'s &amp; <del>your</del>
                  <persName ref="#ps:MaryAugustaWard"><add place="above">M<hi rend="superscript"
                           >rs</hi></add> Humphry Ward's</persName>, not yours.</p>
            </postscript>




         </div>
